EDA | LFB Incident Records | Project 1 Summary¶

Introduction:¶

The London Fire Brigade (LFB) is the fire and rescue service for London. As of August 2021, it is the busiest and largest of all fire services across the United Kingdom.

The purpose of this exploratory data analysis is to provide insight into the incident records of the LFB from 2009 onwards. Incidents include actual fire, false alarms, lift releases, water leakage within buildings and even suicide attempts. We will explore, for example, time of call, incident type, property type, location and response time. Concurrently, we will make use of the gained knowledge in cleaning, reducing and wrangling our data.

The preprocessed data can then be used for modelling, perhaps in another project segment.

If you have spotted a mistake, or have any comments or enquiries regarding my projects, please don't hesitate to contact me at nghugoryan(at)gmail(dot)com.

Conclusion:¶

  • Overall, we have seen a slight drop in the number of false alarm and fire incidents over the years. Cases tend to peak during summer and late afternoon.
  • When we look at false alarm and fire incidents, 70% of them were false alarm incidents. In our breakdown, we find that properties that contributed most to false alarms had a significant proportion of events coming from Automatic Fire Alarms.
  • Most incidents concentrated in the very center of London. Westminster Southwark, Tower Hamlets and Camden were the top four incident prone regions among 32 boroughs and the City of London. They together accounted for 22% of incidents. These were the areas that are the most resource intensive, as they saw the most mobilization.
  • The expected response time (FirstPumpArriving_AttendanceTime) across different hours were quite stable, remaining between 295 to 330 seconds throughout the hours.
  • The median response time across different classifications of address qualifiers ranged from a 200 to 400 seconds, except for motorways / elevated roads, which had a median of 500 seconds, which is over 8 minutes. We believe this is because motorways / elevated roads are not as accessible compared to other properties. Also, When the reported address of an incident was more accurate, the response time was quicker as we would expect.
  • Across commissioned grounds of each fire station, a range of 91% to 56% of cases were handled by the corresponding fire station. The remaining cases were handled by other fire stations.

Call to action:¶

  • Further investigation should be conducted to see if there are any fire-causing or alarm-causing activities done specifically during summer and late afternoon. If so, measures from, for example, the government, fire department or property owners are needed to curtail these risks.
  • There is a desire for engineering companies and manufacturers to better calibrate or even re-invent automatic fire alarms to improve their accuracy, because many false alarms come from automatic fire alarms. Doing so, fire departments can better respond to actually dangerous events.
  • There might be a need to allocate more resources to the central parts of London, since these areas see the most incidents and calls.
  • Fire stations might consider using the breakdown of event type (primary fire, secondary fire, etc) by property category (vehicles, residential buildings, etc) to better arm themselves with suitable equipment. For example, outdoor incidents are associated with secondary fires, and vehicles are associated with primary fires. It may be beneficial if fire stations prepare different sets of equipment according to this analysis on incident types, before any incidents actually occur. When mobilization is needed, they can load the needed sets of equipment for a best response to incidents.
  • Automation or invention is needed to bring down the cost of monitoring or responding to hard-to-access motorways, such that fire incidents can be quickly addressed. This is to solve the dilemma in resource allocation for motorway incidents, since they don't contribute much to total numbers, but have slow response time due to inaccessibility.
  • Measures to improve location reporting accuracy during emergency calls should be implemented, since an accurate location is vital for quick response time. This may be done automatically or manually. For example, there is a need to better promote geocode systems, such as what3words (a proprietary geocode system designed to accurately pinpoint any location, which emergency services now accept) to the general public. These can then be used in emergency situations.
  • For some fire stations, up to 45% of cases in their own commissioned grounds are handled by other fire stations. Investigation by the fire department is needed to see if this is an optimal strategy, or if this is the manifestation of poor management.

1. Numerical or ordinal categorical features :¶

Histogram¶

(Cell 33 in Project 1 GitHub repository ipynb)

Interpretation of the above results:¶
  • There was a noticeable drop in the number of fire related incidents (real fire/ false alarms) from 2009 to 2014, followed by a plateau or very slight increase from 2015 to 2020. For 2021, we must bear in mind that its records are not complete. Hence the number of incidents for the year 2021 is distinctly small. When you view this markdown, these records might have been updated. You should similarly take the number of incidents for the last year with a grain of salt.
  • Cases peaked towards summer(May-Sep), with a gradual drop moving away (forwards/backwards) from summer, until reaching a valley in Feb. Since we have removed records in the last year for Months, we can rest assured that the partial records in the last year (records only up to a certain month) does not contribute to the plot, and hence will not skew the plot with an increase in numbers for the earlier months. It may be possible to correspond an increase of fire related incidents with weather patterns in the summer (eg higher heat) or activities done in the summer.
  • Cases are significantly high around 12:00 to 21:00, with a peak at 18:00. Outside of these hours, the number of cases fall sharply. It may be possible to correspond an increase of fire related incidents with activities done in the afternoon. However, we should also remember that there is inherently more activity in daylight hours as most people work in the day, hence such increase can also be purely natural.
Histogram, kernel density plot and boxplot¶

(Cell 34 in Project 1 GitHub repository ipynb)

Interpretation of the above results:¶
  • Histogram and kernel density plot (upper):
    • In the orange scaled histogram of response time, we have a skewed peak in count around 250 seconds (a bit over 4 minutes), with gradual drops towards both the 0 second end and the 1200 second end. The many sharp spikes at certain values likely come from rounding, where some collection of incidents might not have FirstPumpArriving_AttendanceTime precise down to unit seconds. Hence, certain values can see large clumps.
    • The red line is the kernel density plot corresponding to the scaled histogram. The density plausibly resembles a skewed Gaussian distribution, as it matches the boundary of the scaled histogram well. Such underlying distribution may be, for example, ex Gaussian, log Gaussian, or inverse Gaussian. Appropriate hypothesis tests can be conducted to test the significance of each of these distributions.
  • Boxplot (lower):
    • In the boxplot, the box represents the IQR, with whiskers extending from Q(1)-1.5*IQR to Q(3)+1.5*IQR. Outside of the whiskers there are seemingly thick lines. These are in fact many overlapping outliers in diamond shape.
    • With many observations (>740000), it is natural for this many outliers to appear. Further, if the underlying distribution is indeed Gaussian related, then many outliers are actually expected. This is because such Gaussian related distribution should have a wide support from 0 to positive infinity.

2. Nominal categorical features¶

Histogram¶

(Cell 36 in Project 1 GitHub repository ipynb)

Now we plot histograms for each nominal categorical variable. From our detailed analysis at Project 1 GitHub repository ipynb, we know some categories have many unique values. Hence, displaying everything results in clutter. We will only display at most the top 6 most frequent values for each category.

Interpretation of the above results:¶
  • IncidentGroup:
    • Most fire related incidents are false alarms (around 70%). The remaining are actual fire incidents. Recall we have partitioned IncidentGroup and put all special service incidents from combined_df in df_S. Hence, there are no special service incidents here.
  • StopCodeDescription:
    • Around half of all incidents are set off by automatic fire alarms. 20% of all incidents are false alarms (good intent or malicious) reported by people, and the remaining 30% are actual fire.
    • Side note: AFA in StopCodeDescription means automatic fire alarm.
  • PropertyCategory:
    • Dwelling and non-residential buildings account for the majority of incidents. However we need to account for the fact that most properties are of these two types. Hence, it might not be that these properties are inherently more prone to fire. Otherwise, the remaining incidents come from, for example, outdoors, other residential buildings such as hotels, and vehicles.
  • PropertyType:
    • There doesn't seem to be anything particularly interesting. However, note that the top 6 values of PropertyType only account for around 40% of all values. Hence, incidents are rather evenly spread across different values.
  • AddressQualifier:
    • Firefighters are correctly informed of over half of all cases. But this also means that many cases do not have a precise reported location.
  • IncBoroughName:
    • Westminster, being the core of Central London, accounts for over 8% of all fire related incidents of London. Otherwise, incidents are rather evenly spread across other boroughs.
  • FRS:
    • Almost all fire related incidents in London are dealt with internally by the fire and rescue services in London, ie the London Fire Brigade. Otherwise, the remaining 0.4% of cases are dealt with by services from outside.
  • IncidentStationGround:
    • Soho, being the main entertainment district of Westminster, accounts for the most incidents among all station grounds, where a station ground is the region a particular fire station monitors. Otherwise, incidents are rather evenly spread across other station grounds.
  • FirstPumpArriving_DeployedFromStation:
    • Again, the Soho station ground accounts for most deployment. Since the top four values in IncidentStationGround correspond exactly with FirstPumpArriving_DeployedFromStation, we have strong reason to believe that stations, most of the time, respond to their own monitored regions.

Interpretation of the above results:¶
  • The central part of London tend to have the highest number of cases, with Westminster accounting for >60000 cases. All three boroughs with >30000 cases (Southwark, Tower Hamlets and Camden) are in very close proximity to the very centre of London. Of the central part, the only region with under 20000 cases is the City of London. However, we can explain this phenomenon in the next point.
  • When looking at the map, we should bear in mind that boroughs/regions come in different sizes. It is natural for bigger boroughs to contain more people and/or properties, and hence see more cases. This also explains why the City of London, being the tiniest region, although located in the very centre of London where we would expect a lot of cases, in truth has very few cases.
  • To account for region sizes, we can conduct another analysis where we divide the number of cases in a region by the region size. Doing so, we look at the concentration of cases in each region, rather than just the absolute number. Such adjustment better informs us which regions are actually more prone to fire or false alarm incidents.

(Cell 49 in Project 1 GitHub repository ipynb)

We analyze how the mean FirstPumpArriving_AttendanceTime (average response time to false alarms or fires) vary over months and years, from 2009 onwards.

We consider:

  • a month as the interval size.
  • the entire London area for the mean FirstPumpArriving_AttendanceTime

Below, we will

  1. Use train_F_chrono, which has observations sorted in chronological order of DateOfCall
  2. Filter out observations with missing FirstPumpArriving_AttendanceTime
  3. Extract month and year from DateOfCall and group, keeping the above order unchanged
  4. Create a lineplot of FirstPumpArriving_AttendanceTime against MonthYear

Interpretation of the above results:¶

We know that a lower response time is better.

The expected first pump arriving attendance time (response time) fluctuates around 260 seconds and 360 seconds. There is no obvious trend across the months and years from 2010 onwards.

Also note that the peaks and valleys of the above line graph are exaggerated for easy distinction. If we were to set the lower y-axis limit of the plot to 0, then the plot line is quite close to a flat line.

We consider:

  • an hour as the interval size.
  • the entire London area for the mean FirstPumpArriving_AttendanceTime

Interpretation of the above results:¶

We know that a lower response time is better.

The expected first pump arriving attendance time (response time) ranges from 295 seconds to 330 seconds. Valleys occur around 9am and 10pm. Otherwise, attendance time gradually increases away from these two hour marks, reaching peaks near 4am and 3pm.

2. Numerical to categorical features¶

2i. FirstPumpArriving_AttendanceTime and AddressQualifier¶

(Cell 51 in Project 1 GitHub repository ipynb)

Interpretation of the above results:¶

We know that a lower response time is better.

The seaborn violin plot is a combination of a boxplot and a kernel density plot. In our graph, the kernel densities are colored, and the boxplots are the bars inside each violin.

The first pump arriving attendance times (AddressQualifier) (response time) across different qualities of reported location, except On motorway / elevated road, have medians (white dot inside each violin) within 200 and 400 seconds. They share similar interquartile ranges (thick lines within each violin) and upper and lower adjacent values (thin lines within each violin).

The exception of On motorway / elevated road has a median around 500 seconds, a greater interquartile range, a higher upper adjacent value and a smaller lower adjacent value.

As we would expect, when the reported location is less precise, the response time goes up and can be more varied. In this case, precision can be determined by the size of the reported area and the distance from the actual location.

Also, when the reported location is harder to reach, the response time also goes up. For example, motorways, elevated roads or open land/water, compared to usual streets, take more time to reach from fire stations.

2ii. HourOfCall and PropertyCategory¶

(Cells 52-53 in Project 1 GitHub repository ipynb.)

Let's review the unique values of PropertyCategory:

Currently, there are 24 hour levels and 9 unique values of PropertyCategory (excluding missing values). If we plot a side-by-side bar chart, with each group containing PropertyCategories and spread across 24 hour levels, we will end up with 24×9=216 bars. There are too many to visualize on a single plot

The strategy will be to

  • homogenize 4 hour intervals
  • homogenize Road Vehicle, Rail Vehicle, Boat and Aircraft as Vehicles due to their low counts

This results in 6×6=36 bars only.

Interpretation of the above results:¶

The number of incidents across different property categories rise and fall follow a similar trend, rising and falling as HourOfCall vary. Such trend is similar to what we see in the histogram for HourOfCall of the univariate analysis of train_F_chrono.

We see that the major contributor to fire incidents across the hours are Dwelling, Vehicles and Outdoor. These peak during late afternoon hours. Further investigation can be done to find if there is any significant correlation between property categories across the hours. This allows London fire departments to better understand city dynamics, and hence better strategize depending on the hours.

For false alarms, across the hours, there is high contribution from Non Residential and Outdoor, and some contribution from Dwelling. Otherwise, other properties do not contribute much.

Interpretation of the above results:¶

Fire stations vary by how many percent of cases within their own commissioned ground they actually handle by themselves. Such percentage varies from over 90% to 50%.

For instance, the Addington fire station handles 90.82% of cases within its ground, but the Dockhead fire station only handles 57.55% of cases within its ground.

Further investigation by the fire department should be conducted to see if there is an over-reliance of certain fire stations on other fire stations, or whether this reliance is actually optimal.

5. Conclusion and call to action¶

Conclusion:¶

  • Overall, we have seen a slight drop in the number of false alarm and fire incidents over the years. Cases tend to peak during summer and late afternoon.
  • When we look at false alarm and fire incidents, 70% of them were false alarm incidents. In our breakdown, we find that properties that contributed most to false alarms had a significant proportion of events coming from Automatic Fire Alarms.
  • Most incidents concentrated in the very center of London. Westminster Southwark, Tower Hamlets and Camden were the top four incident prone regions among 32 boroughs and the City of London. They together accounted for 22% of incidents. These were the areas that are the most resource intensive, as they saw the most mobilization.
  • The expected response time (FirstPumpArriving_AttendanceTime) across different hours were quite stable, remaining between 295 to 330 seconds throughout the hours.
  • The median response time across different classifications of address qualifiers ranged from a 200 to 400 seconds, except for motorways / elevated roads, which had a median of 500 seconds, which is over 8 minutes. We believe this is because motorways / elevated roads are not as accessible compared to other properties. Also, When the reported address of an incident was more accurate, the response time was quicker as we would expect.
  • Across commissioned grounds of each fire station, a range of 91% to 56% of cases were handled by the corresponding fire station. The remaining cases were handled by other fire stations.

Call to action:¶

  • Further investigation should be conducted to see if there are any fire-causing or alarm-causing activities done specifically during summer and late afternoon. If so, measures from, for example, the government, fire department or property owners are needed to curtail these risks.
  • There is a desire for engineering companies and manufacturers to better calibrate or even re-invent automatic fire alarms to improve their accuracy, because many false alarms come from automatic fire alarms. Doing so, fire departments can better respond to actually dangerous events.
  • There might be a need to allocate more resources to the central parts of London, since these areas see the most incidents and calls.
  • Fire stations might consider using the breakdown of event type (primary fire, secondary fire, etc) by property category (vehicles, residential buildings, etc) to better arm themselves with suitable equipment. For example, outdoor incidents are associated with secondary fires, and vehicles are associated with primary fires. It may be beneficial if fire stations prepare different sets of equipment according to this analysis on incident types, before any incidents actually occur. When mobilization is needed, they can load the needed sets of equipment for a best response to incidents.
  • Automation or invention is needed to bring down the cost of monitoring or responding to hard-to-access motorways, such that fire incidents can be quickly addressed. This is to solve the dilemma in resource allocation for motorway incidents, since they don't contribute much to total numbers, but have slow response time due to inaccessibility.
  • Measures to improve location reporting accuracy during emergency calls should be implemented, since an accurate location is vital for quick response time. This may be done automatically or manually. For example, there is a need to better promote geocode systems, such as what3words (a proprietary geocode system designed to accurately pinpoint any location, which emergency services now accept) to the general public. These can then be used in emergency situations.
  • For some fire stations, up to 45% of cases in their own commissioned grounds are handled by other fire stations. Investigation by the fire department is needed to see if this is an optimal strategy, or if this is the manifestation of poor management.
